1124. iter viai: so in ii. 626 ‘iter viarum '. For viai cf. 1. 946.

1126. invidia: either the envy of unsuccessful rivals (certantes, 1. 1124) or more probably, as Duff suggests, ‘this invidia bears some resemblance to the Nemesis or envy of the gods in the old mythology, which Lucretius utterly discards ’. In the same way in ll. 1136-40 Nemesis falls on kings, and in ll. 1231—2 on fleets. For the same reason, when a man was uncertain whether to marry a rich lady above him in rank or a poor one of his own position, Pittacus, the sage, advised him to choose the latter, telling him to watch children spinning their tops in the street ancl saying each to his own top τὴν κατὰ σαυτὸν ἔλαυνε, ⁴ keep in your own line '.
